		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27963165">For those not familiar with the series, Maria-sama is a character study set in a Japanese Catholic school for girls where etiquette and tradition are at the center of everything. It is an unusual backdrop in anime to say the least, especially due to the amalgamation of Western and Eastern culture: the character portrayals are Japanese at heart, but pervaded by Christian values. Reflecting this in particular are the <em>Souer</em> relationships, which compose the core motif of the story. In essence, it revolves around the concept of bonding people through a relationship of mutual understanding and support, where a senior student (referred as 'sister') guides an underclassman (referred as 'little sister') both in and outside of the classroom. As the previous descriptions suggest, the bonds are of a sisterly nature; they delineate a strong sense of intimacy, and this is reflected in the character interactions in a truly beautiful manner. The appeal of such bonds is not limited to how they are conveyed though; witnessing them slowly being threaded is also wonderful, much thanks to the delicate pacing and subtle character building. In this sense, Maria-sama's slow paced approach is similar to Saraiya Goyou's, particularly the way it develops backgrounds for the characters and their relationships through gradually integrated backstories. A few of them are poorly structured and might come out as melodramatic, unfortunately. But all in all, they do an excellent job at laying out and strengthening the cast's interpersonal dynamics; the particularities they reveal are also of great importance in understanding the characters' motivations. Of course, there is a lot of flair added to the mix—particularly the yuri undertones—but thanks to how things are paced and presented, they are anything but obtrusive and actually feel like an ingrained part of the relationships: something that naturally happened over time. This is how yuri should be done: subtly and as something that is defined by the relationship and not the inverse. <br />
<br />
One important thing to note is that while the drama is often triggered by silly misunderstandings, the characters always manage to resolve their differences through dialogue and mutual understanding; here the solid foundations upon which the relationships are built become evident. The resolutions are rarely complex, but behind their simplicity they carry a lot of subtle meaning. <br />
<br />
Maria-sama 3rd retains much of the charm and character of the previous seasons, but there are a couple important differences that should be noted. First of all, the drama is largely toned down and the episodes are even more slice of life oriented; we are still presented with the same characters, but in a more everyday context. The change of tone is undeniably positive, and even without the intricate character drama of the second season, the writing remains as strong as ever. One of the things that make this season successful is the wide array of scenarios and situations never explored in the series before. What most shines under these circumstances is the dynamics between the characters—they are at a point of their relationship where they truly understand each other (as if they are together in their own world), so watching them interact in a different context in their own unique way is fascinating to say the least. Much of this is goes hand in hand with the character growth carried on from the previous seasons, with the characters reacting to situations and environments in manners that would be inconceivable in the past—the development is strongly cumulative. <br />
<br />
Second, this season has evidently superior production values than its prequels. While Maria-sama isn't the kind of anime that requires particularly fluid movement, the inconsistent animation would occasionally hinder the effectiveness of the characters' body language and give an awkward impression. Thankfully, the third season has great character animation, doing a fairly better job at conveying the emotional state of the characters. Art direction, too, is very solid, doing a particularly commendable job in regards to scenery (the Venezia episode was on par with Origination when it comes to scenery pr0n and atmosphere building). The music, on the other hand, while not particularly improved, remains as graceful as ever. And more importantly, it remains in tone with how the show depicts school life, creating a soundscape of classical instrumentation that is perfectly befitting of the elegance and serenity that so deeply permeates the Lillian Girls' Academy.  <br />
<br />
In conclusion, this anime is goddamn good. Go watch it now!!!<br />
<br />
(this text is wordy as hell and probably needs editing and I'm also leaving out a lot of stuff I know but it can't be helped)</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by Parial, 01-25-14, 11:35 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
