		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28003981">Parial did an excellent job at providing an overview to the Maria-sama ga Miteru franchise, so my post will focus on the third season (which is arguably the best installment in my view) along with some background information on the two leading ladies. <br />
<br />
The first thing to note about MariMite 3rd is that it's almost entirely centered on the show's primary soeur pair, Yumi and Sachiko. Although the other sisters are still prominent figures in every episode (Yoshino &lt;3), they sort of take a backseat as most of the external events relate to the development of Yumi and Sachiko's relationship. And speaking of their relationship, what a beautifully complex one they have at that. On one end, you have Yumi, who is about as average as girls her age come (though don't bother asking me how to measure averageness in a 15-year old Japanese Catholic girl). Whereas on the other, you have Sachiko - who is a prim, elegant and astonishingly beautiful young lady from a wealthy household - basically, the polar opposite of Yumi. Through a series of unexpected conveniences, but ultimately a heartfelt connection, Yumi ends up becoming Sachiko's soeur - an event she could have never dreamed of, even in, well, her wildest dreams. <br />
<br />
As one might expect, a relationship between two girls from two completely different backgrounds would be anything but peaches and roses - perhaps an assorted mixture of sweet and spicy chocolates would make for a better metaphor. Within a fairly short span of time, the formality of their sisterly ritual begins to wear thin as Yumi doubts her worth as Sachiko's soeur - leading to some brief bouts of avoidance, miscommunication and temporary rifts between the two. But with pain comes understanding, and it is only through this that the two are able to become more intimate as a result. You see, although Yumi and Sachiko are complete opposites on a surface level, they both share a common flaw as emotional human beings - that they keep a lot of their feelings bottled up, and do not initially rely on the support of each other to sort out their issues. <br />
<br />
As the seasons change from spring to summer, a gentle breeze signals a period of warmth and relaxation. But beyond that, it is a precious time for Yumi and Sachiko to bond, to reconcile, and above all, to enjoy life together. <br />
<br />
The major differences between MariMite 3rd and the previous installments are the length of each episode (clocking in at 50 minutes, as opposed to the standard 24), and the slight change in tone from the dramatic to the natural. As a result, this provides proper exposure to the pair's relationship, carefully detailing their daily activities and most intimate conversations instead of simply skipping ahead to the episode's conflict. That's not to say the OVA is free from the occasional silly drama (some of which is unfortunately a bit unnecessary), but in general the smooth pacing and gradual build up irons out any jarring mood shifts that its predecessors had. Likewise, by adopting a more down to earth approach, the OVA places greater emphasis on the characters' more subtle nuances, taking great care to convey them as realistically as possible. For instance, a scene where Sachiko vents her frustration caused by some snobby socialites is made all the more convincing by the amount of detail in her body language. Her ire is conveyed exceptionally well by the crossness of her facial expression, the tenseness of her posture and the anger in her tone of voice (on a side note, Miki Itou's performance is completely spot-on for Sachiko's character type). As Yumi approaches her and attempts to lend a helping hand, you can see Sachiko's initial reluctance as she maintains distance and averts her gaze - a defensive mechanism used to shut herself off from others, and easily the cause of many of her interpersonal problems. However, after Yumi continues to interject, you can slowly see the change in Sachiko's demeanor, as she relaxes and opens herself up to Yumi, and to communication. It's a powerful display of the pair's trust, and it's the combined effect of similar memorable scenes that gives the OVA a very understated, beautiful quality.<br />
<br />
And if we want to get really technical with definitions of "beautiful", MariMite 3rd boasts some very high quality production values (something that may be a bit uncharacteristic of Studio DEEN). Gone are the days of animation inconsistencies, as the OVA maintains an incredibly polished look throughout - picturesque backgrounds and fluid character movements a plenty. The general art direction is also handled well, with special attention given to the lighting, framing and especially some of the <!--link--><a href="http://i.imgur.com/iLUvgZD.jpg" rel="nofollow">scene layouts</a>. The soundtrack also deserves a special mention, for its evocative classical-infused score and solid timing of pieces to suit the quaint and serene atmosphere. <br />
<br />
Above all, MariMite 3rd thoroughly explores the cast in a meaningful way, placing it above many other character-driven works. Sachiko, who initially comes across as cold, strict and aloof is shown to be a much more caring and vulnerable person than her princess image would suggest. As a result, not only does she become a more likable character, but we can now understand the rationale behind many of her previous actions. Likewise, Yumi's time spent with her older sister has a very pronounced effect on her overall being (though the method in which the anime portrays these changes is quite subtle). Most of the idol worship she had for Sachiko is now gone, as she no longer views her as being on a higher plane, but rather someone she can actively trust and confide in. Being separated still causes her some anxiety (in the last episode), but she is able to work through this with the help of her other friends and ultimately emerge as a more independent young woman.  <br />
<br />
Overall, Maria-sama ga Miteru 3rd (and by extension, the entire series) is a beautiful display of character intimacy, along with one of the most complex and well-realized casts in any anime. The series now has a special place in my heart for most of the reasons I've listed above, and I'd highly recommend it to people that appreciate series with realistic characters and mild inklings of shoujo-ai that are never overbearing.<br />
<br />
<!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>Parial said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>In conclusion, this anime is <strong>goddamn</strong> good. Go watch it now!!!<!--quote--></div><br />
